article.description: Bonzi Wells got the boos Wednesday night. Then he got the points.
article.headline: Gasol chips in 15 points and 10 boards
article.linkText: Bonzi takes boos, gets last laugh in Portland
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- It wasn't about revenge against Portland. Bonzi Wells said he was trying to guard against another Seattle. Wells scored 25 points Wednesday night to give the Memphis Grizzlies their first road win of the season, a 101-82 victory Wednesday night over his former team, the Portland Trail Blazers. Wells, known during his time in Portland for his uneven temperament and inconsistent play, was peppered with boos throughout the game, which Memphis led by as many as 34 points. Memphis had struggled with blowing leads, evident Sunday when the team squandered a 21-point second-half advantage to lose 118-113 to the SuperSonics. "I told the guys, `We're not going to have an instant replay of the Seattle game. If we get down 20, we're going to try to get it to 30," he said. "And that is what we did." After the loss, the Blazers huddled behind closed doors. "Any team that gets beat like that is going to talk about it," Portland center Theo Ratliff said. "There didn't need to be any finger pointing. Everybody got beat." The Grizzlies, who started the season with four straight losses, have a pair of wins at home. But they had lost all three of their previous road games. That wasn't to be at Portland's Rose Garden Arena. Pau Gasol added 15 points and 10 rebounds for the Grizzlies. Zach Randolph had 16 points and seven rebounds for the Blazers, who only shot 39.2 percent. Wells was booed by the sparse weeknight crowd during introductions, but was then hugged warmly by Randolph at tipoff. He went on to score 15 points in the first half against his former team, including a 3-pointer that swished from the corner to make it 45-33, and the Grizzlies led 53-40 at the break. Wells had a turbulent five-plus seasons in Portland before he was traded to Memphis last December. His play was streaky, and he never emerged as the team leader many had hoped he would be. He also had a few run-ins with Maurice Cheeks and was suspended for two games before the trade for cursing at the coach. He was fined by the team for making an obscene gesture toward a fan at the Rose Garden earlier in the season. Shane Battier hit a 3-pointer to put the Grizzlies up 66-52, and the Blazers couldn't come up with any kind of rhythm to mount a threat. At that point the fans turned their boos to the Blazers. When Wells left the game with a little more than 6 minutes to go, Memphis coach Hubie Brown patted him on the shoulder. Then Wells high-fived his teammates on the bench, one by one. "It is always good to play against a team you used to play for," Wells said. "I just tried to do whatever it takes for my team to win. I got the shots going good." The Blazers, meanwhile, played out the game before retreating sullenly to the locker room. "I've never been on a team where we cleared so much air. We clear air every other day," guard Nick Van Exel said. "I've been in a lot of meetings but it doesn't so any good if you don't go out and incorporate it in your attitude and your game."

Game notes
The Grizzlies hope to get guard James Posey back by Monday's game at home against San Antonio. Posey has missed five games with a strained left foot. Before his injury, he had played in 179 straight games. ... Current Blazer Shareef Abdur-Rahim is still the Grizzlies' career leader in points (7,801), scoring average (20.8) and rebounds (3,070).
